{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486767"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"170"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/170"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.11,0.01,0.26,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39376"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/170"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23744"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6417"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42013"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39376"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department after a motor bike crash. He complains of severe pelvic pain. There are no other apparent injuries and he can recall the crash details clearly. On examination, his blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg and pulse 100/min. He has a palpable, distended bladder and any pressure on the pelvis produces considerable pain. An plain X-ray of the pelvis confirms an open book fracture of the pelvis. The patient wants to void, but is unable to do so and is not in any obvious distress. Some blood is visible at the urinary meatus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suprapubic catheter","Urethral catheter","Stand patient up to facilitate voiding","Retrograde urethrogram","CT scan abdomen and pelvis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWith blood visible at the external urinary meatus associated with a pelvic fracture, the possibility of urethral injury should be strongly considered. Whilst urethral injuries are not common, when they do occur, over 80% of cases are associated with pelvic fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA pelvic fracture with palpable bladder and blood at the urethral meatus always needs a r\u003Cstrong\u003Eetrograde urethrogram\u003C/strong\u003E performed. If the urethra is intact, then a catheter can be passed. \u003Cstrong\u003EA suprapubic catheter\u003C/strong\u003E in a patient with a pelvic fracture should be avoided unless absolutely necessary. These fractures often need a plate put in to close their \u0022open book\u0022 fracture. Urine leak from a suprapubic catheter can lead to infected metalwork and disaster.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlind passage of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eurethral catheter\u003C/strong\u003E could worsen the situation and convert a partial tear into a complete tear. If there is no evidence of urethral injury, a urethral catheter can be passed - otherwise this patient will require suprapubic bladder catheterisation. Trying to \u003Cstrong\u003Estand a patient up\u003C/strong\u003E who has a pelvic fracture is impractical. Further imaging, such as a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E, is not going to help him void and will not give as clear visualisation of the lower urinary as a urethrogram. This should be the next step in his management. If the patient had an urgent need to void and it was causing him distress, then a suprapubic catheter might be appropriate. Otherwise, without that degree of urgency, a urethrogram should be performed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pelvic trauma and the inability to void must always raise the possibility of urethral injury."],"references":["Battaloglu E, Figuero M, Moran C, et al. Urethral injury in major trauma. Injury, Int J Care Injured 2019; 50:1053-57."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"170"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-09-14T12:46:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T18:57:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"170"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39376"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7